benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/catalog - Retrieve the catalog as JSON

covered: Valid requests: Default/latest, requestedDate, accountId, both-parameters and partial-parameter retrievals are covered (TC01, TC02, TC03, TC04, TC16, TC20).
Response format & headers: Content-Type application/json and that the body is a JSON array of Catalog objects are asserted (TC01, TC23).

Query-parameter validation: Good coverage for valid and invalid requestedDate and accountId formats, unsupported parameters are ignored, and edge dates are considered (TC02, TC07, TC03, TC08, TC11, TC17).
Empty / no-data handling: No-catalog and no-catalog-for-requested-date scenarios return 404 and are covered (TC05, TC06).
Error handling: Client errors and server-side errors are covered (400 for invalid input, 401 for auth, 503 for dependent service, 504 for timeout) (TC07, TC08, TC09, TC10, TC14, TC22).
Performance & scalability: Large dataset response time and concurrent request behavior are exercised (TC12, TC13).
Large payload and edge-case robustness: Very large catalog payloads and non-truncation are covered (TC18).
Security input validation: Malicious input / SQL-injection style query is tested (TC15).
Resilience & regression: Retry/recovery, regression and backward compatibility tests are included (TC21, TC19, TC20).
Schema / machine-readability: A scenario asserts machine-readable JSON and compliance with the API schema (TC23).
gaps: Pagination: No tests for pagination parameters or paginated responses (page/limit, offsets) or behavior when datasets are split across pages.
Caching behavior / conditional GET: No tests for ETag, Last-Modified, Cache-Control headers, or conditional requests (If-None-Match, If-Modified-Since) to validate caching semantics.
Rate limiting / throttling: No tests exercise rate limits or assert 429 behavior when request rate is exceeded; TC13 covers concurrency but not throttling limits.
Authorization granularity: 403 / permission-denied cases are not covered (role/permission-based access), only 401 (missing/invalid token) is tested.
Content negotiation: No tests for Accept header variations (requests asking for non-JSON, or checking server behavior when Accept is absent/unsupported).

Response schema enforcement: Although the response is asserted to be a JSON array, there are no explicit schema-validation tests that assert required Catalog fields, types, and constraints (deep JSON schema checks).
Error response contract: Tests do not assert a consistent error payload format (error code structure, fields, machine-readable error schema).
Rate-limiting under concurrency / DoS: TC13 tests concurrency performance but does not simulate/exercise rate-limiting or denial-of-service protection behavior.
recommendations: Add pagination tests: if the API can return large catalogs, include page/limit/offset tests, validate pagination headers, and ensure correct ordering and completeness across pages.
Add caching and conditional GET tests: assert ETag and Cache-Control headers, and test If-None-Match / If-Modified-Since behavior (304 responses) and cache freshness semantics.
Add rate-limiting tests: simulate bursts and sustained high request rates to verify 429 responses and backoff behavior; include tests that exercise rate limits under concurrency.
Add authorization/permission tests: include 403 scenarios (authenticated but unauthorized) if the API has tenant/role restrictions; verify tenant isolation when accountId is provided.
Add content-negotiation tests: send Accept: application/xml and other headers to verify the server either returns 406 or correctly falls back to JSON; assert Content-Type is honored.
Add strict schema validation: validate the response against the canonical JSON schema for Catalog (required fields, types, nested structures) to catch semantic regressions.
Assert error response contract: add tests that validate the error body structure for 4xx/5xx responses (error codes, messages, fields) so clients can rely on a stable error contract.
Extend performance tests to include streaming/pagination interplay and large-response transfer behavior (Content-Length, chunked transfer) and verify no truncation under high load.
